Highlight

The scheduled Monthly Treasury Statement release dates for 2025 are listed on the back of this publication.

November has been a deficit month 70 times out of 71 fiscal years since there are no major tax due dates in this month.

Outlays for military active duty and retirement, veterans benefits, Supplemental Security Income, and Medicare payments to health maintenance organizations and prescription drug plans accelerated into November, because December 1, 2024, the normal payment date, fell on a non-business day.

Introduction

The Monthly Treasury Statement of Receipts and Outlays of the United States Government (MTS) is prepared by the Bureau of the Fiscal Service, Department of the Treasury and, after approval by the Fiscal Assistant Secretary of the Treasury, is normally released on the 8th workday of the month following the reporting month. The publication is based on data provided by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.

AUDIENCE

The MTS is published to meet the needs of those responsible for or interested in the cash position of the Treasury, those who are responsible or interested in the Government's budget results; and individuals and businesses whose operations depend upon or are related to the Government's financial operations.

DISCLOSURE STATEMENT

This statement summarizes the financial activities of the Federal Government and off-budget Federal entities conducted in accordance with the Budget of the U.S. Government, i.e., receipts and outlays of funds, the surplus or deficit, and the means of financing the deficit or disposing of the surplus. Information is presented on a modified cash basis; receipts are accounted for on the basis of collections; refunds of receipts are treated as deductions from gross receipts; revolving and management fund receipts, reimbursements and refunds of monies previously expended are treated as deductions from gross outlays; and interest on the public debt (public issues) is recognized on the accrual basis. Major information sources include accounting data reported by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.

TRIAD OF PUBLICATIONS

The MTS is part of a triad of Treasury financial reports. The Daily Treasury Statement is published each working day of the Federal Government. It provides data on the cash and debt operations of the Treasury based upon reporting of the Treasury account balances by Federal Reserve banks. The MTS is a report of Government receipts and outlays, based on agency reporting. The Combined Statement of Receipts, Outlays, and Balances of the United States Government is the official publication of the detailed receipts and outlays of the Government. It is published annually in accordance with legislative mandates given to the Secretary of the Treasury.

DATA SOURCES AND INFORMATION

The Explanatory Notes section of this publication provides information concerning the flow of data into the MTS and sources of information relevant to the MTS.

## Highlight

The scheduled Monthly Treasury Statement release dates for 2025 are listed on the back of this publication.

November has been a deficit month 70 times out of 71 fiscal years since there are no major tax due dates in this month.

Outlays for military active duty and retirement, veterans benefits, Supplemental Security Income, and Medicare payments to health maintenance organizations and prescription drug plans accelerated into November, because December 1, 2024, the normal payment date, fell on a non-business day.

## Introduction

*The Monthly Treasury Statement of Receipts and Outlays of the United States Government (MTS)* is prepared by the Bureau of the Fiscal Service, Department of the Treasury and, after approval by the Fiscal Assistant Secretary of the Treasury, is normally released on the 8th workday of the month following the reporting month. The publication is based on data provided by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.

## AUDIENCE

The *MTS* is published to meet the needs of those responsible for or interested in the cash position of the Treasury, those who are responsible or interested in the Government's budget results; and individuals and businesses whose operations depend upon or are related to the Government's financial operations.

## DISCLOSURE STATEMENT

This statement summarizes the financial activities of the Federal Government and off-budget Federal entities conducted in accordance with the Budget of the U.S. Government, i.e., receipts and outlays of funds, the surplus or deficit, and the means of financing the deficit or disposing of the surplus. Information is presented on a modified cash basis; receipts are accounted for on the basis of collections; refunds of receipts are treated as deductions from gross receipts; revolving and management fund receipts, reimbursements and refunds of monies previously expended are treated as deductions from gross outlays; and interest on the public debt (public issues) is recognized on the accrual basis. Major information sources include accounting data reported by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.

## TRIAD OF PUBLICATIONS

The *MTS* is part of a triad of Treasury financial reports. The *Daily Treasury Statement* is published each working day of the Federal Government. It provides data on the cash and debt operations of the Treasury based upon reporting of the Treasury account balances by Federal Reserve banks. The *MTS* is a report of Government receipts and outlays, based on agency reporting. The *Combined Statement of Receipts, Outlays, and Balances of the United States Government* is the official publication of the detailed receipts and outlays of the Government. It is published annually in accordance with legislative mandates given to the Secretary of the Treasury.

## DATA SOURCES AND INFORMATION

The Explanatory Notes section of this publication provides information concerning the flow of data into the *MTS* and sources of information relevant to the *MTS.*

Highlight

The scheduled Monthly Treasury Statement release dates for 2025 are listed on the back of this publication.

November has been a deficit month 70 times out of 71 fiscal years since there are no major tax due dates in this month.

Outlays for military active duty and retirement, veterans benefits, Supplemental Security Income, and Medicare payments to health maintenance organizations and prescription drug plans accelerated into November, because December 1, 2024, the normal payment date, fell on a non-business day.

Contents

Introduction

The Monthly Treasury Statement of Receipts and Outlays of the United States Government (MTS) is prepared by the Bureau of the Fiscal Service, Department of the Treasury and, after approval by the Fiscal Assistant Secretary of the Treasury, is normally released on the 8th workday of the month following the reporting month. The publication is based on data provided by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.

AUDIENCE

The MTS is published to meet the needs of those responsible for or interested in the cash position of the Treasury, those who are responsible or interested in the Government's budget results; and individuals and businesses whose operations depend upon or are related to the Government's financial operations.

DISCLOSURE STATEMENT

This statement summarizes the financial activities of the Federal Government and off-budget Federal entities conducted in accordance with the Budget of the U.S. Government, i.e., receipts and outlays of funds, the surplus or deficit, and the means of financing the deficit or disposing of the surplus. Information is presented on a modified cash basis; receipts are accounted for on the basis of collections; refunds of receipts are treated as deductions from gross receipts; revolving and management fund receipts, reimbursements and refunds of monies previously expended are treated as deductions from gross outlays; and interest on the public debt (public issues) is recognized on the accrual basis. Major information sources include accounting data reported by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.

TRIAD OF PUBLICATIONS

The MTS is part of a triad of Treasury financial reports. The Daily Treasury Statement is published each working day of the Federal Government. It provides data on the cash and debt operations of the Treasury based upon reporting of the Treasury account balances by Federal Reserve banks. The MTS is a report of Government receipts and outlays, based on agency reporting. The Combined Statement of Receipts, Outlays, and Balances of the United States Government is the official publication of the detailed receipts and outlays of the Government. It is published annually in accordance with legislative mandates given to the Secretary of the Treasury.

DATA SOURCES AND INFORMATION

The Explanatory Notes section of this publication provides information concerning the flow of data into the MTS and sources of information relevant to the MTS.

document.description: This is a financial report about the U.S. government's receipts and outlays
document.summary: This document is the Monthly Treasury Statement of Receipts and Outlays of the United States Government for November 2024 and other periods. It provides detailed information on the government's financial activities, including receipts by source, outlays by function, and the overall surplus or deficit. The report is published by the Bureau of the Fiscal Service, Department of the Treasury, and is based on data from federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks. It is intended for those responsible for or interested in the government's cash position, budget results, and financial operations.

representation.text:
Highlight

The scheduled Monthly Treasury Statement release dates for 2025 are listed on the back of this publication.

November has been a deficit month 70 times out of 71 fiscal years since there are no major tax due dates in this month.

Outlays for military active duty and retirement, veterans benefits, Supplemental Security Income, and Medicare payments to health maintenance organizations and prescription drug plans accelerated into November, because December 1, 2024, the normal payment date, fell on a non-business day.

Contents

Summary	Page 5
Receipts	Page 10
Outlays	Page 11
Means of Financing	Page 25
Receipts/Outlays by Month	Page 35
Federal Trust Funds/ Securities	Page 37
Receipts by Source/Outlays by Function	Page 38
Explanatory Notes	Page 39

Introduction

The Monthly Treasury Statement of Receipts and Outlays of the United States Government (MTS) is prepared by the Bureau of the Fiscal Service, Department of the Treasury and, after approval by the Fiscal Assistant Secretary of the Treasury, is normally released on the 8th workday of the month following the reporting month. The publication is based on data provided by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.

AUDIENCE

The MTS is published to meet the needs of those responsible for or interested in the cash position of the Treasury, those who are responsible or interested in the Government's budget results; and individuals and businesses whose operations depend upon or are related to the Government's financial operations.

DISCLOSURE STATEMENT

This statement summarizes the financial activities of the Federal Government and off-budget Federal entities conducted in accordance with the Budget of the U.S. Government, i.e., receipts and outlays of funds, the surplus or deficit, and the means of financing the deficit or disposing of the surplus. Information is presented on a modified cash basis; receipts are accounted for on the basis of collections; refunds of receipts are treated as deductions from gross receipts; revolving and management fund receipts, reimbursements and refunds of monies previously expended are treated as deductions from gross outlays; and interest on the public debt (public issues) is recognized on the accrual basis. Major information sources include accounting data reported by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.

TRIAD OF PUBLICATIONS

The MTS is part of a triad of Treasury financial reports. The Daily Treasury Statement is published each working day of the Federal Government. It provides data on the cash and debt operations of the Treasury based upon reporting of the Treasury account balances by Federal Reserve banks. The MTS is a report of Government receipts and outlays, based on agency reporting. The Combined Statement of Receipts, Outlays, and Balances of the United States Government is the official publication of the detailed receipts and outlays of the Government. It is published annually in accordance with legislative mandates given to the Secretary of the Treasury.

DATA SOURCES AND INFORMATION

The Explanatory Notes section of this publication provides information concerning the flow of data into the MTS and sources of information relevant to the MTS.

3

![Title: Monthly Receipts, Outlays, and Budget Deficit/Surplus of the U.S. Government, Fiscal Years 2024 and 2025
The chart displays monthly financial data for the U.S. government across fiscal years 2024 and 2025. It shows three key components: receipts (green bars), outlays (blue bars), and the resulting deficit/surplus (orange bars). The data reveals consistent monthly deficits, with outlays typically exceeding receipts. There are notable spikes in both receipts and outlays during certain months, particularly April, which shows a significant surplus. The scale ranges from -$1,000B to $1,000B for the main metrics, with the deficit/surplus scale ranging from -$600B to $200B.

![Title: U.S. Government Receipts by Source, Month of November 2024
The pie chart shows the breakdown of U.S. Government receipts for November 2024, totaling $302B. Social Insurance and Retirement Receipts represent the largest portion at $138B, followed by Individual Income Taxes at $131B. Corporation Income Tax accounts for $9B, while Excise Taxes contribute $10B. Other sources amount to $9B, and Miscellaneous Receipts make up $4B of the total. The chart provides a clear visualization of the relative proportions of different revenue streams for the U.S. Government during this period.

representation.text: The Monthly Treasury Statement of Receipts and Outlays of the United States Government (MTS) is prepared by the Bureau of the Fiscal Service, Department of the Treasury and, after approval by the Fiscal Assistant Secretary of the Treasury, is normally released on the 8th workday of the month following the reporting month. The publication is based on data provided by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.
representation.markdown: *The Monthly Treasury Statement of Receipts and Outlays of the United States Government (MTS)* is prepared by the Bureau of the Fiscal Service, Department of the Treasury and, after approval by the Fiscal Assistant Secretary of the Treasury, is normally released on the 8th workday of the month following the reporting month. The publication is based on data provided by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.

The publication is based on data provided by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.

representation.text: AUDIENCE
representation.markdown: ## AUDIENCE
representation.html: AUDIENCE

representation.text: The MTS is published to meet the needs of those responsible for or interested in the cash position of the Treasury, those who are responsible or interested in the Government's budget results; and individuals and businesses whose operations depend upon or are related to the Government's financial operations.

representation.text: DISCLOSURE STATEMENT
representation.markdown: ## DISCLOSURE STATEMENT
representation.html: DISCLOSURE STATEMENT

representation.text: This statement summarizes the financial activities of the Federal Government and off-budget Federal entities conducted in accordance with the Budget of the U.S. Government, i.e., receipts and outlays of funds, the surplus or deficit, and the means of financing the deficit or disposing of the surplus. Information is presented on a modified cash basis; receipts are accounted for on the basis of collections; refunds of receipts are treated as deductions from gross receipts; revolving and management fund receipts, reimbursements and refunds of monies previously expended are treated as deductions from gross outlays; and interest on the public debt (public issues) is recognized on the accrual basis. Major information sources include accounting data reported by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.

representation.text: TRIAD OF PUBLICATIONS
representation.markdown: ## TRIAD OF PUBLICATIONS
representation.html: TRIAD OF PUBLICATIONS

representation.text: The MTS is part of a triad of Treasury financial reports. The Daily Treasury Statement is published each working day of the Federal Government. It provides data on the cash and debt operations of the Treasury based upon reporting of the Treasury account balances by Federal Reserve banks. The MTS is a report of Government receipts and outlays, based on agency reporting. The Combined Statement of Receipts, Outlays, and Balances of the United States Government is the official publication of the detailed receipts and outlays of the Government. It is published annually in accordance with legislative mandates given to the Secretary of the Treasury.

The *MTS* is a report of Government receipts and outlays, based on agency reporting. It is published annually in accordance with legislative mandates given to the Secretary of the Treasury.

representation.markdown:
![Title: Receipts, Outlays, and Surplus/Deficit Analysis for November 2024 and FY2025
The image shows two Sankey diagrams comparing federal budget flows. Figure 1 displays November 2024 data with total receipts of $302 billion and outlays of $669 billion, resulting in a $367 billion deficit. The main revenue sources are Individual Income Taxes ($138B) and Social Insurance & Retirement ($131B). Major outlays include Medicare ($129B), Social Security ($125B), and Health ($80B). Figure 2 shows cumulative figures through FY2025, with total receipts of $629 billion and outlays of $1,253 billion, creating a $624 billion deficit. The spending priorities remain similar but with larger amounts, led by Social Security ($250B) and Medicare ($206B).

Title: Monthly Receipts of the U.S. Government, by Source, Fiscal Years 2024 and 2025

elements.summary:
Title: Monthly Outlays of the U.S. Government by Source, Fiscal Years 2024 and 2025
The stacked bar chart shows U.S. government monthly outlays from October 2024 to November 2025, broken down by seven major spending categories: Social Security, Medicare, Health, National Defense, Income Security, Net Interest, and Other. Total outlays for November 2024 were $669B, with fiscal year 2025 to date reaching $1,253B. The spending is represented in billions of dollars, with values ranging from approximately $300B to $700B per month. The "Other" category encompasses various government functions including Administration of Justice, Agriculture, Education, Energy, and Veterans' Benefits among others. The chart demonstrates monthly variations in spending patterns across these categories, with consistent base spending in areas like Social Security and Medicare.

text_lines.text: The scheduled Monthly Treasury Statement release dates for 2025 are listed on the back of this publication.
November has been a deficit month 70 times out of 71 fiscal years since there are no major tax due dates in this month.
Outlays for military active duty and retirement, veterans benefits, Supplemental Security Income, and Medicare
payments to health maintenance organizations and prescription drug plans accelerated into November, because
December 1, 2024, the normal payment date, fell on a non-business day.
The Monthly Treasury Statement of Receipts and Outlays of the United States Government (MTS) is prepared by the Bureau
of the Fiscal Service, Department of the Treasury and, after approval by the Fiscal Assistant Secretary of the Treasury, is
normally released on the 8th workday of the month following the reporting month. The publication is based on data provided
by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.
The MTS is published to meet the needs of those responsible for or interested in the cash position of the Treasury, those who
are responsible or interested in the Government's budget results; and individuals and businesses whose operations depend
upon or are related to the Government's financial operations.
This statement summarizes the financial activities of the Federal Government and off-budget Federal entities conducted in
accordance with the Budget of the U.S. Government, i.e., receipts and outlays of funds, the surplus or deficit, and the means
of financing the deficit or disposing of the surplus. Information is presented on a modified cash basis; receipts are accounted
for on the basis of collections; refunds of receipts are treated as deductions from gross receipts; revolving and management
fund receipts, reimbursements and refunds of monies previously expended are treated as deductions from gross outlays; and
interest on the public debt (public issues) is recognized on the accrual basis. Major information sources include accounting data
reported by Federal entities, disbursing officers, and Federal Reserve banks.
The MTS is part of a triad of Treasury financial reports. The Daily Treasury Statement is published each working day of the
Federal Government. It provides data on the cash and debt operations of the Treasury based upon reporting of the Treasury account
balances by Federal Reserve banks. The MTS is a report of Government receipts and outlays, based on agency reporting. The
Combined Statement of Receipts, Outlays, and Balances of the United States Government is the official publication of the detailed
receipts and outlays of the Government. It is published annually in accordance with legislative mandates given to the Secretary of the
The Explanatory Notes section of this publication provides information concerning the flow of data into the MTS and sources
of information relevant to the MTS.
